  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Community Managed Disaster Risk Reduction in St. Maarten</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In the days after the passing of hurricane Irma, there was a wide range of issues related to getting much needed food, water and other supplies to residents throughout St. Maarten. Despite its best efforts, the Government of St. Maarten was unable to reach thousands of residents. When the full extent of these difficulties became evident, the Government attempted to use community councils as an avenue for reaching residents. However, as the councils have had no experience in emergency response, or community mobilization they were unable to efficiently or effectively reach the residents of their communities. Moreover, as the Government has had little formal dialogue or collaboration with the community councils, there was no existing relationship to build upon during the immediate disaster response period, further limiting support for residents.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The objective of this project is to increase the capacities of community councils throughout St. Maarten and support the development of community-driven emergency preparedness and response. In doing so, this project will improve community and national resilience throughout St. Maarten by strengthening the local community structures, strengthening social networks and improving the relationship with Government to ensure all residents are served.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The program will target 15 community councils throughout St. Maarten. The Community Councils are key components of St. Maarten&#x2019;s civil society. These organizations were incorporated over a decade ago and were to serve as a voice of the residents of the communities they serve. As the voice of their communities, these organizations were to represent community interest, and act as intermediaries towards facilitating better communication between the government and the people of St. Maarten. Other not-for-profit foundations and associations exist throughout the island; however, the community councils are the only organizations established specifically to be representative of residents at a community level.

Indirectly, this project will positively impact approximately 10,000 residents across St. Maarten. While this project focuses on the approximately 75 members of the various community councils that will participate throughout the programming period, the activities to be executed such as community mobilization, community engagement, hazard mapping and vulnerability identification will be to the benefit of all residents. Moreover, the increased collaboration with Government to provide public services directly to residents will benefit all.</narrative>
  </description>
